ke Constance]]\n| [[Internationale Rheinregulierungsbahn]]\n| Construction railway for the regulation works of the river Rhine near its outfall into Lake Constance, now preserved. The river forms the border between Austria and Switzerland, and the railway operated in both countries.\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil]]\n| [[Rio de Janeiro]]\n| [[Rio de Janeiro Metro]]\n| Lines 1, 2 and 4\n|-\n| [[S\u00e3o Paulo]]\n| [[S\u00e3o Paulo Metro]]\n| Lines 1, 2, 3 and 15 (monorail), 17 (future, monorail)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Karlsruhe]] to [[Bad Herrenalb]] with a branch to [[Ittersbach]]\n| [[Alb Valley Railway|Albtalbahn]]\n| railway of the Upper Rhine\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| [[Genoa|Genova]]\n| [[Metropolitana di Genova]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | {{flagicon|Japan}} Japan\n| [[Hamamatsu, Shizuoka]]\n| [[Enshu Railway Line|Ensh\u016b Railway]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Hakone, Kanagawa]]\n| [[Hakone Tozan Line|Hakone Tozan Railway Line]]\n| between Hakone-Yumoto and G\u014dra\n|-\n| [[Ehime Prefecture|Ehime]]\n| [[Iyo Railway|Iyotetsu]] [[Iyotetsu Yokogawara Line|Yokogawara Line]] and [[Iyotetsu Gunchu Line|Gunch\u016b Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Yokkaichi, Mie]]\n| [[Yokkaichi Asunarou Railway]] [[Yokkaichi Asunarou Railway Utsube Line|Utsube Line]], [[Yokkaichi Asunarou Railway Hachi\u014dji Line|Hachi\u014dji Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Mie Prefecture|Mie]]\n| [[Sangi Railway Hokusei Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|MEX}} [[Mexico]]\n| [[Mexico City]]\n| [[Sistema de Transporte Colectivo|STC]]\n| [[Mexico City Metro Line A|Line A]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|NLD}} [[Netherlands]]\n| [[The Hague]], [[Zoetermeer]], [[Rotterdam]] and adjacent cities\n| [[Randstadrail]]\n| &nbsp;\n|- \n| [[Rotterdam]]\n| [[Rotterdam Metro]]\n| North of Capelsebrug station overhead wires\n|-\n| rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Philippines}} [[Philippines]]\n| [[Metro Manila]]\n| [[Manila LRT Line 1]] ([[Manila Light Rail Transit System]])\n| between [[Baclaran station|Baclaran]] to [[Roosevelt station (Line 1)|Roosevelt]]\n|-\n| [[Metro Manila]]\n| [[Manila MRT Line 3]] ([[Manila Metro Rail Transit System]])\n| between [[North Avenue station (Line 3)|North Avenue]] to [[Taft Avenue station|Taft Avenue]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n| [[Canton of Aargau]]\n| [[Wynental- und Suhrentalbahn|Wynental- und Suhrentalbahn (WSB)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Turkey]]\n| [[Adana]]\n| [[Adana Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Istanbul]]\n| [[Istanbul Metro]]\n| Line [[M1 (Istanbul Metro)|M1]], [[M2 (Istanbul Metro)|M2]], [[M6 (Istanbul Metro)|M6]] \n|}\n\n====1,200 V DC====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Notes\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Cuba}} [[Cuba]]\n| [[Havana]] \u2013 [[Matanzas]] and branches\n| [[Ferrocarriles Nacionales de Cuba]]\n| originally (and still known as) the [[Hershey Electric Railway]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Estonia]]\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| (Elektriraudtee) 1924\u20131941 and 1946\u20131958, converted to 3000 V DC\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Lusatia]]n\n| &nbsp;\n| {{RailGauge|900 mm}} gauge mining railways in the [[lignite]] district\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain\n| [[Barcelona]], [[Catalonia]]\n| [[Barcelona Metro]]\n| uses an [[overhead conductor rail]]/beam system\n|-\n| [[Palma, Majorca|Palma]] \u2013 [[S\u00f3ller]], [[Majorca]]\n| [[Ferrocarril de S\u00f3ller|S\u00f3ller Railway]]\n|<ref>[http://www.sollernet.com/trendesoller/ S\u00f3ller Website]</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=6 | {{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n| [[Canton of Bern]] / [[canton of Solothurn]]\n| [[Aare Seeland mobil|Aare Seeland mobil (ASm)]]\n| {{sfnp|Schweers+Wall|2012|p=11}}{{sfnp|Schweers+Wall|2012|p=19}}\n|-\n| [[Dietikon]], [[canton of Z\u00fcrich]] \u2013 [[Wohlen, Aargau|Wohlen]], [[canton of Aargau]]\n| [[Bremgarten-Dietikon-Bahn]]\n| \n