S subways.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eef;\"\n| Using this type of electrification\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| No longer using this type of electrification\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background:#eef; width:100%; border:0;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%\" | Type\n! style=\"width:18%\" | Country\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:15%\" | Location\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:22%\" | Name of system\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:30%\" | Notes\n|-\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|Argentina}} [[Argentina]]\n| Buenos Aires\n| [[L\u00ednea Urquiza (Buenos Aires)|Urquiza Line]]\n| [[Federico Lacroze railway station|Federico Lacroze]]-General Lemos\n|-\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} Canada\n| Toronto\n| [[Toronto Subway and RT|Toronto Subway and Rapid Transit]]\n| only on subway lines\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|Greece}} Greece\n| Athens\n| [[Athens-Piraeus Electric Railways|EIS/ISAP]]\n| used between 1904 and 1985\n|-\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| Turin\n| [[Superga Rack Railway]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| Top contact\n|rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Japan}} Japan\n| Tokyo\n| [[Tokyo Metro]] [[Tokyo Metro Ginza Line|Ginza Line]] and [[Tokyo Metro Marunouchi Line|Marunouchi Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| &nbsp;\n| [[Nagoya, Aichi|Nagoya]], [[Aichi Prefecture|Aichi]]\n| [[Nagoya Municipal Subway]] [[Higashiyama Line]] and [[Meij\u014d Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden\n| Stockholm\n| [[Stockholm Metro]]\n| 650 V, Green and Red Lines\n|-\n| Top contact\n| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| Glasgow\n| [[Glasgow Subway]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| Top contact\n|rowspan=7| {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| Boston\n| [[Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority]]\n| Red and Orange Lines, the subway part of the Blue Line southwest of [[Airport (MBTA station)|Airport Station]]\n|-\n| Top contact\n| Chicago\n| [[Chicago \"L\"]]\n| elevated and subway lines\n|-\n| Top contact\