it (Singapore)|Light Rail Transit]]\n| [[Sengkang LRT Line]] and [[Punggol LRT Line]] operated by [[SBS Transit]]\n|-\n| [[Singapore]]\n| [[Sentosa Express]]\n| [[Sentosa Express]] operated by [[Sentosa Development Corporation|SDC]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]]\n| [[Las Vegas Monorail]]\n| &nbsp;\n|}\n\n===== Top contact =====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ; style=width:100%\n|-\n! style=\"width:21%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:34%\" | Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|China}} China\n| [[Beijing]]\n| [[Beijing Subway]]\n| Capital Airport Line use button contact \n|-\n| [[Tianjin]]\n| [[Tianjin Metro]]\n| Line 1 only\n|-\n| {{flagicon|France}} France\n| [[Paris]]\n| [[Paris M\u00e9tro]] ([[Metro (rapid transit)|Conventional metro]])\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Berlin]]\n| [[Berlin U-Bahn]]\n| Lines from U1 to U4 (small profile)\n|-\n| {{flagicon | Greece}} Greece\n| [[Athens]]\n| [[Athens Metro]]\n| Line 1 was 600 V before 1985.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Hungary}} Hungary\n| [[Budapest]]\n| [[Budapest Metro]]\n| except line M1, which is 600 V DC with overhead lines.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|India}} India\n| [[Kolkata]]\n| [[Kolkata Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |{{flagicon|Japan}} Japan\n| [[Osaka, Osaka]]\n| [[Osaka Metro]]\n| except the [[Sakaisuji Line]], [[Nagahori Tsurumi-ryokuchi Line]], and the [[Imazatosuji Line]], which are 1,500 V DC with overhead lines.\n|-\n| [[Suita, Osaka]]<br />[[Toyonaka, Osaka]]\n| [[Kita-Osaka Kyuko Railway]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Higashiosaka, Osaka]]<br />[[Ikoma, Nara]]<br />[[Nara, Nara]]\n| [[Kintetsu Railway|Kintetsu]] [[Keihanna Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Yokohama, Kanagawa]]\n| [[Yokohama Municipal Subway]]\n| [[Blue Line (Yokohama)|Blue Line]] (Line 1 and Line 3) only\n|-\n| {{flagicon|North Korea}} [[North Korea]]\n| [[Pyongyang]]\n| [[Pyongyang Metro]]\n| based on fleet of cars from Beijing and Germany\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n| [[Yongin]]\n| [[Everline]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[Portugal]]\n| [[Lisbon]]\n| [[Lisbon Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Puerto Rico}} [[Puerto Rico]]\n| [[San Juan, Puerto Rico|San Juan]]\n| [[Tren Urbano]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Sweden}} Sweden\n| [[Stockholm]]\n| [[Stockholm Metro]]\n| Nominal voltage 650 V, subway 3 (blue line) 750 V. Subway 1 and 2 will change in the long term to 750 V.\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |{{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| [[Liverpool]]\n| [[Merseyrail]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[London]]\n| [[Northern City Line]]\n| access to City (Moorgate)\n|-\n| [[London]]\n| [[Suburban electrification of the London, Midland and Scottish Railway|LNWR Suburban Network]]\n| formerly four-rail out of Euston and Broad Street, curtailed, upgraded and standardised\n|-\n| Southern England\n| [[Southern Region of British Railways]] and successors\n| 660 V system upgraded and expanded\n|-\n| rowspan=9 | {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| [[Atlanta, Georgia]]\n| [[MARTA]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Los Angeles, California]]\n| [[Los Angeles Metro Rail]]\n| [[Red Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Red]] and [[Purple Line (Los Angeles Metro)|Purple]] Lines\n|-\n| [[Miami, Florida]]\n| [[Metrorail (Miami-Dade County)|Metrorail]]\n|\n|-\n| [[New York City]] and [[Long Island]]<br />[[East River Tunnels]] shared with [[Amtrak]]\n| [[Long Island Rail Road]]\n| [[Central Branch (LIRR)|Central]], [[Greenport Branch|Greenport]], and [[Oyster Bay Branch|Oyster Bay]] branches not electrified; [[Montauk Branch]] not electrified east of [[Babylon station|Babylon]]; [[Port Jefferson Branch]] not electrified east of [[Huntington (LIRR station)|Huntington]]\n|-\n| [[Philadelphia, PA]]\n| [[PATCO Speedline]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Puerto Rico]]\n| [[Tren Urbano]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Washington, D.C.]]\n| [[Washington Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| within the [[North River Tunnels|Hudson]] and [[East River Tunnels]] as well as under [[Manhattan]]<br />[[Northeast Corridor]]\n| [[Amtrak]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| within the [[North River Tunnels|Hudson Tunnel]] into [[Manhattan]]\n| [[Northeast Corridor Line|New Jersey Transit]]\n| &nbsp;\n|}\n\n===== Mixed =====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eef;\"\n| Using this type of electrification\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| No longer using this type of electrification\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"background:#eef; width:100%; border:0;\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:15%\" | Type\n! style=\"width:18%\" | Country\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:15%\" | Location\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:22%\" | Name of system\n! class=\"unsortable\" style=\"width:30%\" | Notes\n|-\n| See note\n| {{flagicon|China}} China\n| [[Tianjin]]\n| [[Tianjin Metro]]\n| Top contact in Line 1, bottom contact in Lines 2 and 3\n|}\n\n====1200 V DC conductor====\n\nAll systems are third rail unless stated otherwise.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eef;\"\n| Using this type of electrification\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| No longer using this type of electrification\n|}\n\n=====Side contact=====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" ; style=width:100%\n|-\n! style=\"width:21%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:34%\" | Notes\n|- style=\"background:#eef;\"\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} [[Germany]]\n| [[Hamburg]]\n| [[Hamburg S-Bahn]]\n| 15 kV/16.7 Hz with overhead line in part of network.\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| {{flagicon|UK}}[[United Kingdom]] \n| Manchester \n| [[British Rail Class 504|Manchester-Bury]] \n| Dismantled 1991, converted to [[Manchester Metrolink]] tramway (750 V DC overhead)\n|}\n\n==Systems using non-standard voltages==\n\n===Overhead systems===\n\n====DC voltage====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:12%\" | Voltage\n! style=\"width:18%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:18%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:18%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Notes\n|-\n| 120