 Railway]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 1125\n| 50&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland\n| [[Interlaken]]\n| [[Jungfraubahn]]\n| \n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| rowspan=2 | 3600\n| 15&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| [[Northern Italy]]\n| [[Valtellina#Industrial|Valtellina]] Electrification\n| 1902\u20131917\n|-\n| 50&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|France}} France\n| [[Saint-Jean-de-Luz]] to [[Larrun]]\n| [[Chemin de Fer de la Rhune]]\n| &nbsp;\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 3600\n| 16&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Switzerland}} Switzerland, {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| [[Simplon Tunnel]]\n| &nbsp;\n| 1906\u20131930\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| rowspan=2 | 3600\n| rowspan=2 |{{frac|16|2|3}}&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Italy}} [[Three-phase AC electrification of Ferrovie dello Stato|Italy]]\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| operated 1912\u20131976 in Upper Italy (more info needed)\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| [[Porrettana railway]]\n| [[Ferrovie dello Stato|FS]]\n| 1927\u20131935\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 3600\n| {{frac|16|2|3}}&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| Trento/Trient to Brenner \n| [[Brenner Railway]]\n| 1929 - 1965\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 5200\n| 25&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain\n| [[Almeria]] \u2013 [[Gergal]]\n| &nbsp;\n| 1911\u20131966?\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 6600\n| 25&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| [[Cascade Tunnel]]\n| [[Great Northern Railway (U.S.)]]\n| 1909 - 1929\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 10&nbsp;kV\n| 45&nbsp;Hz, 3\u00d8\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| [[Rome|Roma]] - [[Sulmona]]\n| [[Ferrovie dello Stato|FS]]\n| 1929\u20131944<ref>{{cite journal |last=Cacozza |first=Marco |title=Three-Phase Electrification: An Italian Story |publisher=Today's Railways Europe #248 |date=August 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n===== Three wires =====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:10%\" | Voltage\n! style=\"widt