iro - Bartolom\u00e9 Mitre<br />Retiro - [[Tigre, Buenos Aires|Tigre]]\n|-\n| [[Once Station|Once]] - [[Moreno, Buenos Aires|Moreno]]\n| [[Sarmiento Line]]\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | 850\n| rowspan=2 | third rail\n| {{flagicon|France}} France\n| Villefranche\n| [[Ligne de Cerdagne]]\n| Often referred to as the \"Yellow Train\"\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Austria}} Austria\n| [[Vienna]]\n| [[Wiener Lokalbahn]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n|900\n| third rail\n| {{flagicon|Belgium}} Belgium\n| Brussels\n| [[Brussels Metro]]\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=4 |1500\n| third rail\n| rowspan=4 | {{flagicon|China}} China\n| Guangzhou\n| [[Line 4, Guangzhou Metro|Guangzhou Metro Line&nbsp;4]], [[Line 5, Guangzhou Metro|Line&nbsp;5]] and [[Line 6, Guangzhou Metro|Line&nbsp;6]]\n| Overhead wires in depots; all trains are equipped with pantographs\n|-\n| third rail\n| Shenzhen\n| [[Longgang Line, Shenzhen Metro|Shenzhen Metro Line 3]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| third rail\n| Shanghai\n| [[Line 16, Shanghai Metro|Shanghai Metro Line&nbsp;16]]\n| Overhead wires in depot; all trains are equipped with pantographs\n|-\n| third rail\n| Beijing\n| [[Line 7, Beijing Subway|Beijing Subway Line&nbsp;7]]\n| \n|-\n|}\n\n==Special or unusual types==\n\n===DC, plough collection from conductors in conduit below track===\n{{Main article|Conduit current collection}}\n* [[London County Council Tramways]], later operated by [[London Passenger Transport Board|London Transport]]\n* [[Third Avenue Railway|streetcars in New York City (Manhattan), New York]]\n* [[Streetcars in Washington, D.C.|Washington, D.C. streetcars]]\n* [[Panama Canal locks#Mules|Panama Canal locks']] ship handlers (called ''mules'')\n\n===DC, one ground-level conductor===\n*Wolverhampton Corporation Tramways, England (stud contact) (1902\u20131921)\n*[[Tramway de Bordeaux|Bordeaux Tramway]], France ([[Ground level power supply#Use in Bordeaux|conductor rail]])\n* Sydney Light Rail (tramway)(Under construction)\n\n===DC, two-wire===\n*[[Greenwich]], England. Previously used by trams when in the vicinity of [[Greenwich Observatory]]; separate from trolleybus supply.\n*[[Cincinnati, Ohio]], US. Tram (streetcar) system used this arrangement throughout, probably due to legal constraints on ground return currents.\n*[[Havana]] and [[Guanabacoa]], Cuba. Tram (streetcar) systems in both cities used this arrangement.\n*[[Lisbon]], Portugal. [[Elevador da Bica]], [[Elevador da Gl\u00f3ria]] and Elevador da Lavra.\n\n===DC, power from running rails===\n* [[Gross-Lichterfelde Tramway]] (1881\u20131893), 180 V\n* [[Ungerer Tramway]] (1886\u20131895)\n* transportable railways as a ride for children\n\n===DC, four-rail===\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! Voltage\n! Type\n! Contact system\n! Name of system\n! Location\n! Country\n! Notes\n|-\n| rowspan=5| 750\n| rowspan=3| [[guide bar]]s\n| lateral to both guide bars (one guide connected to [[Rail profile|running rail]])\n| [[Paris Metro]]\n| [[Paris]]\n| France\n| [[Rubber-tyred metro|rubber-tyred]] lines only\n|-\n| rowspan=2| Lateral (positive) and top of running rails (negative) contact\n| [[Montreal Metro]]\n| [[Montreal]]\n| Canada\n| rubber-tyred lines\n|-\n| [[Mexico City Metro]]\n| [[Mexico City]]\n| Mexico\n| rubber-tyred lines\n|-\n| rowspan=3| [[Third rail|Third]] and [[fourth rail]]\n| lateral (positive) and top (negative) contact\n| [[Milan Transportation System]]\n| [[Milan]]\n| Italy\n| metro (only line 1)\n|-\n| rowspan=2| Top contact\n| rowspan=2| [[London Underground|London&nbsp;Underground]]\n| rowspan=2| [[London]]\n| rowspan=2| [[United Kingdom|UK]]\n| rowspan=2| Transport for London<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tfl.gov.uk/tube/ |title=Tube &#124; Transport for London |publisher=Tfl.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref>\n|-\n| 630\n|}\n\n==See also==\n{{div col|colwidth=22em}}\n* [[Third rail]]\n* [[Railroad electrification in the United States]]\n* [[Ground level power supply]]\n* [[Conduit current collection]]\n* [[Current collector]]\n* [[Amtrak's 25 Hz traction power system]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* {{citation |url=http://www.bsistandards.co.uk |last=BS EN 50163 |title=EN 50163: Railway applications. Supply voltages of traction systems |year=2007 |publisher=IET |ref=harv |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070213151651/http://www.bsistandards.co.uk/ |archivedate=2007-02-13 }}\n* {{citation |url=http://webstore.iec.ch/webstore/webstore.nsf/mysearchajax?Openform&key=60850&sorting=&start=1&onglet=1 |last=IEC 60850 |title=IEC 60850: Railway applications - Supply voltages of traction systems |edition=3rd |year=2007 |ref=harv}}\n* {{RCTS-LocosLNER-10B}}\n* {{cite book |last=Dixon |first=Frank |title=The Manchester South Junction & Altrincham Railway |edition=2nd |series=The Oakwood Library of Railway History |year=1994 |origyear=1973 |publisher=Oakwood Press |location=Headington |isbn=0-85361-454-7 |id=OL34 |ref=harv }}\n* {{cite book | last=Schweers+Wall |title = Eisenbahnatlas Schweiz | year = 2012 | publisher = Verlag Schweers + Wall GmbH | isbn=978-3-89494-130-7 |ref=harv|id =  {{ASIN|3894941308|country=uk}} }}\n* {{cite book |last=Swain |first=Alec |title=British Rail Fleet Survey 11: Overhead Line Electric Multiple-Units |year=1990 |publisher=[[Ian Allan Publishing|Ian Allan]] |location=Shepperton |isbn=0-7110-1902-9 |ref=harv }}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* http://www.bahnstrom.de/bahnstromsysteme/weltweit_kopf.htm\n* [http://bueker.net/trainspotting/voltage_map_europe.php Map of European voltage-systems]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110519014210/http://www.southernelectric.org.uk/histfeat/seginfohistory.html Southern Electric], England - details of electrification\n\n{{Railway electrification}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:List of railway electrification systems}}\n[[Category:Rail transport-related lists|Electric rail traction]]\n[[Category:Electric power-related lists|Rail]]\n[[Category:Electric rail transport]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikipedia list article}}\nThis is a list of the power supply systems that are, or have been, used for tramway and [[railway electrification system]]s.\n\nNote that the voltages are nominal and vary depending on load and distance from the substation.\n\nMany modern trams and trains use on-board solid-state electronics to convert these supplies to run [[three-phase]] AC induction motors.\n\nTrams electrification systems are listed [[List of tram systems by gauge and electrification|here]].\n\n==Key to the tables below==\n* Volts: [[voltage]] or [[volt]]\n* Current:\n** DC = [[direct current]]\n** xx Hz = [[frequency]] in [[hertz]] ([[alternating current]] (AC))\n*** AC supplies are [[single-phase electric power|single-phase]], except where marked [[three-phase electric power|three-phase]]\n* Conductors:\n**[[overhead line]] or\n**conductor rail, usually a [[third rail]] to one side of the running rails\n*** Conductor rail can be:\n**** top contact: oldest, least safe, affected by ice, snow and leaves\n**** side contact: newer, safer, less affected by ice, snow and leaves\n**** bottom contact: newer, safer, least affected by ice, snow and leaves\n\n==Systems using standard voltages==\n{{see also|Railway electrification system#Voltage}}\n{{see also|List of tram systems by gauge and electrification}}\nVoltages are defined by two standards: BS&nbsp;EN&nbsp;50163{{sfnp|BS EN 50163|2007}} and IEC&nbsp;60850.{{sfnp|IEC 60850|2007}}\n\n===Overhead systems===\n\n====600 V DC====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Notes\n|-\n|colspan=2|{{center|[[World]]}}\n| Many [[tram]] systems\n| This voltage is mostly used by older tram systems worldwide but by a few new ones as well. See [[List of tram systems by gauge and electrification]]\n|-\n| Rowspan=2|{{flagicon|Australia}} Australia\n| [[Adelaide]]\n| [[Trams in 