]], [[canton of Valais]]\n| [[Chemin de fer Aigle\u2013Ollon\u2013Monthey\u2013Champ\u00e9ry|Chemin de fer Aigle\u2013Ollon\u2013Monthey\u2013Champ\u00e9ry (AOMC)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Aigle]] \u2013 [[Les Diablerets]], [[canton of Vaud]]\n| [[Chemin de fer Aigle\u2013S\u00e9pey\u2013Diablerets|Chemin de fer Aigle\u2013S\u00e9pey\u2013Diablerets (ASD)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Interlaken]] \u2013 [[Lauterbrunnen]] / [[Grindelwald]], [[canton of Bern]]\n| [[Berner Oberland Bahn|Berner Oberland Bahn (BOB)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Canton of Jura]]\n| [[Chemins de fer du Jura|Chemins de fer du Jura (CJ)]]\n| [[metre gauge]] lines only; [[standard gauge]] lines are electrified at 15 kV 16 2/3&nbsp;Hz\n|-\n| [[Lausanne]] \u2013 [[Bercher]], [[canton of Vaud]]\n| [[Chemin de fer Lausanne\u2013\u00c9challens\u2013Bercher|Chemin de fer Lausanne\u2013\u00c9challens\u2013Bercher (LEB)]]\n| \n|-\n| [[Nyon]] \u2013 [[La Cure]], [[canton of Vaud]]\n| [[Chemin de fer Nyon-St-Cergue-Morez|Chemin de fer Nyon-St-Cergue-Morez (NStCNM)]]\n| converted in the 1980s from 2200 V DC\n|-\n| [[Vitznau]] / [[Goldau]] \u2013 [[Rigi]]\n| [[Rigi Bahnen|Rigi Bahnen (VRB/ARB)]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Wilderswil]] \u2013 [[Schynige Platte]], [[canton of Bern]]\n| [[Schynige Platte Bahn|Schynige Platte Bahn (SPB)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Liestal]] \u2013 [[Waldenburg, Switzerland|Waldenburg]], [[canton of Basel-Country]]\n| [[Waldenburgerbahn|Waldenburgerbahn (WB)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Lauterbrunnen]] \u2013 [[Grindelwald]], [[canton of Bern]]\n| [[Wengernalpbahn|Wengernalpbahn (WAB)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Turkey}} [[Turkey]]\n| [[Bursa]]\n| [[Bursa Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Istanbul]]\n| [[Istanbul Metro]]\n| Except lines M1, M2 and M6\n|-\n| rowspan=5 | {{flagicon|UK}} [[Railway electrification in Great Britain|United Kingdom]]\n| [[Newcastle upon Tyne|Newcastle]], [[Sunderland, Tyne and Wear|Sunderland]], [[Gateshead]] and [[Tyneside]]\n| [[Tyne and Wear Metro]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[London]] (Liverpool Street) to Shenfield (then Chelmsford)\n| [[Great Eastern Main Line]]\n| Opened in 1949.<br/>Converted to 6.25 kV 50&nbsp;Hz AC in 1960 and later to 25 kV 50&nbsp;Hz AC{{sfnp|Boddy|Fry|Hennigan|Hoole|1990|p=139}}{{sfnp|Swain|1990|p=19}}\n|-\n| [[Manchester]]\n| [[Manchester, South Junction and Altrincham Railway]]\n| Opened in 1931.<br/>Converted to 25 kV 50&nbsp;Hz AC in 1971<br/>Converted again to 750 V DC in 1991 (Metrolink).{{sfnp|Boddy|Fry|Hennigan|Hoole|1990|p=135}}{{sfnp|Dixon|1994|p=119}}\n|-\n| [[Manchester]] to [[Sheffield]]\n| [[Manchester-Sheffield-Wath electric railway|Manchester-Sheffield-Wath]]\n| Operated 1949\u20131984. Abandoned east of {{stnlnk|Hadfield}} in 1981; suburban services in Manchester converted to 25 kV, 50&nbsp;Hz AC as far as Hadfield and [[Glossop railway station|Glossop]] in 1984.{{sfnp|Boddy|Fry|Hennigan|Hoole|1990|ps=, p.101 & p.142}}\n|-\n| [[Shildon]] to Newport\n| [[County Durham]]\n| industrial line; operated 1915\u20131935{{sfnp|Boddy|Fry|Hennigan|Hoole|1990|p=92\u201393}}\n|-\n| rowspan=4 | {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| [[Chicago]]\n| [[Metra Electric District]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Maryland]]\n| [[Maryland Transit Administration]]\n| [[Purple Line (Maryland)|Purple Line]] (under construction)\n|-\n| Northern [[Indiana]] & [[Chicago]]\n| [[South Shore Line]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| [[Seattle]]\n| [[Central Link]]\n| light rail\n|}\n\n====3 kV DC====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Note\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Belgium}} Belgium\n| Nationwide \n| [[National Railway Company of Belgium|Belgium National Railways (SNCB)]]\n| National standard. [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]] used on high speed lines and some lines in the south area.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Brazil}} [[Brazil]]\n| Rio de Janeiro suburban network;\n| SuperVia Trens Urbanos;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} Canada\n| [[Montreal]]\n| [[Deux-Montagnes Line (AMT)|Deux-Montagnes Line]]\n| built by [[Canadian Northern Railway|CNoR]] in 1918, converted to [[25 kV AC, 60 Hz|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC/60&nbsp;Hz]] in 1995 by [[Agence m\u00e9tropolitaine de transport|AMT]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Chile}} [[Chile]]\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| \n|-\n| {{flagicon|Czech Republic}} [[Czech Republic]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Spr\u00e1va \u017eelezni\u010dn\u00ed dopravn\u00ed cesty|Czech Railway Infrastructure Administration (S\u017dDC)]]\n| Northern part of network only (approx. the D\u011b\u010d\u00edn - Praha - Ostrava route). The system change stations are Kada\u0148-Prun\u00e9\u0159ov, Beroun, Bene\u0161ov u Prahy, Kutn\u00e1 Hora hl.n., Svitavy, Nezamyslice, Nedakonice. The southern part uses 25&nbsp;kV 50&nbsp;Hz.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Estonia}} [[Estonia]]\n| [[Tallinn]]\n| [[Elron (rail transit)|Elron]]\n| commuter rail only\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Georgia}} [[Georgia (country)|Georgia]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Georgian Railways|Georgian Railway LLC]]\n| In fact 3,300&nbsp;V\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Italy}} Italy\n| colspan=2 | [[Rete Ferroviaria Italiana|RFI - Rete Ferroviaria Italiana (Italian Railways Network)]]\n| [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]] used on new high speed lines\n|-\n| {{flagicon|North Korea}} [[North Korea]]\n| &nbsp;\n| [[Korean State Railway]]\n| national standard\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Latvia}} [[Latvia]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Latvian Railways|Latvian Railways (LDz)]]\n| commuter rail only, to be converted to 25&nbsp;kV AC which to be intended to connect with Russia, Belarus and Lithuania.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Morocco}} [[Morocco]]\n| &nbsp;\n| ONCF (Office National des Chemins de Fer)\n| national standard\n|-\n| rowspan=2 | {{flagicon|Poland}} [[Poland]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Polish State Railways|Polish State Railways (PKP)]]\n| planned new high-speed lines will use [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]]<ref>{{cite web |author=Micha\u0142 Szymajda |title=Szybka linia kolejowa \u201eY\" przez CPK ma by\u0107 gotowa do 2030 roku |trans-title=High-speed 'Y' railway line through CPK should be completed by 2030 |url=https://www.rynek-lotniczy.pl/wiadomosci/szybka-linia-kolejowa-34y34-przez-cpk-ma-byc-gotowa-do-2030-roku-7669.html |accessdate=5 February 2020 |work=Rynek Lotniczy |date=17 January 2020 |language=pl}}</ref>\n|-\n| [[Warszawa]] and suburbs\n| [[Warszawska Kolej Dojazdowa|Warszawska Kolej Dojazdowa (WKD)]]\n| 600 V DC until 27 May 2016\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Russia}} [[\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f|Russian Federation]]\n| colspan=2 | [[\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0438|Russian Railways (RZD)]]\n| new electrification use only [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]], except Moscow Central Circle and other interconnection lines in Moscow, and 2 interconnection lines (Veymarn line and Kamennogorsk line) in St. Petersberg. For Sverdlovsk railway and West Siberian railway to be converted to 25&nbsp;kV AC.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Slovakia}} [[Slovakia]]\n| colspan=2 | [[\u017deleznice Slovenskej republiky|Slovak Republic Railways (\u017dSR)]]\n| Northern main line (connected to [[Czech Republic]] and [[Poland]]) and eastern lines (around [[Ko\u0161ice]] and [[Pre\u0161ov]]), conversion to [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]] planned, and the broad gauge line between [[Ko\u0161ice]] and the [[Ukraine]] border (it will remain 3&nbsp;kV until new broad gauge line construction, then convert to [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]]), planned new broad gauge line is supposed to use [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]]. Currently, the part north and east of the station P\u00fachov uses 3&nbsp;kV DC, the rest uses 25&nbsp;kV 50&nbsp;Hz.\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Slovenia}} [[Slovenia]]\n| colspan=2 | [[Slovenske \u017eeleznice|Slovenian Railways (S\u017d)]]\n| national standard\n|-\n| {{flagicon|South Africa}} [[South Africa]]\n| colspan = 2 |[[Transnet Freight Rail|Transnet Freight Rail (TFR)]]; [[Metrorail (South Africa)|Metrorail]]\n| national standard; also 25&nbsp;kV AC and 50&nbsp;kV AC used\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Spain}} Spain\n| colspan=2 |ADIF (Administrador de Infraestructuras Ferroviarias)\n| [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]] used on high speed lines\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Ukraine}} [[Transport in Ukraine|Ukraine]]\n| colspan = 2 |[[Ukrainian Railways]]\n| in east (Donetsk industrial zone), in west (west from L'viv \u2013 connecting to Slovakia and Poland), to be converted to [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]]<ref>[[Railway Gazette International]] April 2008, p 240</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|USA}} United States\n| [[New Jersey]], lines towards [[New York City]]\n| [[Morris & Essex Lines]]\n| By [[Delaware, Lackawanna and Western Railroad]] in 1930.<ref>[http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,723751,00.html Electrified D. L. & W.] ''Time magazine archives'' Retrieved 2007-08-12</ref> Converted to [[25 kV AC#60 Hz|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;60&nbsp;Hz]] by [[New Jersey Transit|NJT]] in 1984\n|}\n\n===={{nowrap|15 kV}} AC, {{frac|16|2|3}}&nbsp;Hz / {{nowrap|16.7 Hz}}====\n{{Main article|15 kV AC railway electrification}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Notes\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Austria}} Austria\n| colspan=2 | [[Austrian Federal Railways]]\n| national standard <!-- Planned new high speed lines will near the border use [[25 kV AC railway electrification|25&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC]]: Innsbruck-Italy and broad gauge to Ukraine -->\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| colspan=2 | [[Deutsche Bahn|German National Railways]]\n| national standard\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Norway}} Norway\n| colspan=2 | [[No