3Tangier high-speed rail line]]\n| [[ONCF]]\n| Casablanca\u2013Kenitra section of high-speed rail remains at 3 kV DC<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/africa/single-view/view/africas-first-high-speed-line-inaugurated.html|title=Africa's first high speed line inaugurated|magazine=[[Railway Gazette]]|date=16 November 2018|accessdate=14 December 2018}}</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Namibia}} [[Namibia]]\n| Proposed line to [[Botswana]]\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]]\n| Used on new [[HSL-Zuid|High Speed Lines]] and [[Betuweroute|Freight Lines]]\n| [[Nederlandse Spoorwegen| Dutch Railways (NS)]] \n| 1.5 kV DC used on the rest of the network\n|-\n| rowspan=2| {{flagicon|New Zealand}} New Zealand\n| [[Auckland]]\n| [[Auckland Transport|Auckland suburban]]\n| 77&nbsp;km between Swanson and Papakura; first service 28 April 2014\n|-\n| &nbsp;\n| [[North Island Main Trunk Railway]]\n| Central North Island section, 411&nbsp;km between Palmerston North and Hamilton\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Macedonia}} [[Republic of North Macedonia|North Macedonia]]\n| &nbsp;\n| [[Makedonski \u017deleznici]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Portugal}} [[Portugal]]\n| &nbsp;\n| [[Caminhos de Ferro Portugueses|Portuguese Railways (CP)]]\n| except the [[Linha de Cascais]] (1500 V DC)\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Romania}} [[Romania]]\n| &nbsp;\n| [[Caile Ferate Romane|Romanian Railways (CFR)]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Russia}} [[\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0430\u044f \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044f|Russian Federation]]\n| &nbsp;\n| [[\u041e\u0410\u041e \"\u0420\u043e\u0441\u0441\u0438\u0439\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0435 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u0434\u043e\u0440\u043e\u0433\u0438\"|Russian Railways (RZD)]]\n| National standard\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Saudi Arabia}} [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| [[Haramain high-speed railway]]\n| [[Saudi Railways Organization]]\n| [[Renfe Operadora]] and [[Adif]] will operate th