grid power frequency.\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"width:100%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:20%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:25%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:35%\" | Notes\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Canada}} Canada\n| [[Montreal]]\n| [[Deux-Montagnes Line (AMT)|Deux-Montagnes Line]]\n| built by [[Canadian Northern Railway|CNoR]] in 1918 as 3000 V DC, converted to 25&nbsp;[[Volt|kV]]&nbsp;[[Alternating current|AC]]/60&nbsp;[[Hertz|Hz]] in 1995 by [[Autorit\u00e9 r\u00e9gionale de transport m\u00e9tropolitain|ARTM]]\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Japan}} Japan\n| [[Kant\u014d region|Kant\u014d]] (west of Tokyo), [[Ch\u016bbu region|Ch\u016bbu]], [[Kansai region|Kansai]], [[Ch\u016bgoku region|Ch\u016bgoku]], and [[Kyushu]] regions\n| [[Tokaido Shinkansen|T\u014dkaid\u014d]]-[[Sany\u014d Shinkansen|Sany\u014d]] [[Shinkansen]]<br>[[Hokuriku Shinkansen]] (sections between [[Karuizawa Station|Karuizawa]] - [[J\u014detsumy\u014dk\u014d Station|J\u014detsumy\u014dk\u014d]], and between [[Itoigawa Station|Itoigawa]] - [[Kanazawa Station|Kanazawa]])<br>[[Kyushu Shinkansen]]\n| [[25 kV AC#50 Hz|50&nbsp;Hz]] in eastern Japan; see [[List of railway electrification systems#25 kV AC 50&nbsp;Hz overhead|25 kV AC 50&nbsp;Hz overhead]] above\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |{{flagicon|South Korea}} [[South Korea]]\n| South Korea\n| [[Korail]]\n| all Korail freight/passenger lines except [[Seoul subway]] Line 3 (see [[List of railway electrification systems#1500 V DC overhead|1500&nbsp;V&nbsp;DC overhead]] above)\n|-\n|[[Seoul]]\n|[[Shinbundang Line|Shinbundang line]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Incheon]], [[Seoul]]\n| [[A'REX]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Mexico}} Mexico\n| [[Mexico City]]\n| [[Ferrocarril Suburbano de la Zona Metropolitana del Valle de M\u00e9xico]]\n| &nbsp;<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.fsuburbanos.com/secciones/espacio_viajero/conoce_trenes.php?ver=prestaciones| title=Espacio del Viajero: Conoce los Trenes| quote=Alimentaci\u00f3n (Vcc. catenaria): 25000, 60&nbsp;Hz| language=Spanish| accessdate=24 May 2011| publisher=Ferrocarriles Suburbanos| location=Mexico City }}</ref>\n|-\n| rowspan=2 |{{flagicon|Taiwan}} [[Taiwan]]\n| Taiwan\n| [[Taiwan Railways Administration]]\n| \n|-\n| Western Taiwan\n| [[Taiwan High Speed Railway|Taiwan High Speed Rail]]\n| \n|-\n| rowspan=\"7\" | {{flagicon|United States}} United States\n| [[New Jersey]]\n| [[Morris & Essex Lines]], [[New Jersey Transit]]\n| former {{nowrap|3,000 V DC}} system\n|-\n| [[Aberdeen-Matawan (NJT station)|Aberdeen-Matawan]] to [[Long Branch (NJT station)|Long Branch]], [[New Jersey]]\n| [[North Jersey Coast Line]], [[New Jersey Transit]]\n| Converted in 1978 from [[Pennsylvania Railroad]] {{nowrap|11 kV 25 Hz}} system to the {{nowrap|12.5 kV 25 Hz}} on the Rahway-Matawan ROW and {{nowrap|12.5 kV 60 Hz}} electrification extended to Long Branch in 1988. The Matawan-Long Branch voltage converted from {{nowrap|12.5 kV 60 Hz}} system to the {{nowrap|25 kV 60 Hz}} in 2002.\n|-\n| [[New York City | New York, NY]] to [[Boston]]\n| [[Northeast Corridor|Northeast Corridor (NEC)]], [[Amtrak]]\n| electrified in 2000; see [[Amtrak's 60 Hz traction power system]]\n|-\n| [[Denver]]\n| [[Regional Transportation District|Denver RTD]]\n| opened in 2016; separate 750 V DC system for light rail\n|-\n| [[San Francisco Peninsula]]\n| [[Caltrain]]\n| under construction, expected by 2022; see [[Electrification of Caltrain]]\n|-\n|[[New Mexico]]\n|[[Navajo Mine Railroad]]\n|\n|-\n| [[Texas]]\n| [[Texas Utilities]], Monticello & Martin Lake\n| see [[List of GE locomotives#Electric locomotives|E25B]] and Internet reference<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trainweb.org/southwestshorts/txumonticello.html |title=TXU - Monticello Line |publisher=Trainweb.org |date=1999-11-02 |accessdate=2013-04-22}}</ref>\n|-\n|}\n\n===Conductor rail systems===\n\n====600 V DC conductor====\n\nAll [[third rail]] unless stated otherwise.<br/>\nUsed by most older US subways.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eef;\"