any\n| Lausitzer\n| &nbsp;\n| work line of the [[Lausitzer Braunkohle AG|Lausitzer Brown Coal AG]] company\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} Poland\n| [[Konin]]\n| [[Konin Coal Mine|PAK KWB KONIN]]<ref name=\"locomotives.com.pl\">http://www.locomotives.com.pl/Electric%20Locomotives/EL2.htm</ref>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|Poland}} Poland\n| [[Turek,_Poland|Turek]]\n| [[Adam\u00f3w Coal Mine|PAK KWB ADAM\u00d3W]]<ref name=\"locomotives.com.pl\"/>\n|-\n| {{flagicon|France}} France\n| [[Grenoble]]\n| [[Chemin de fer de La Mure]]\n| \u22121,200&nbsp;V, +1,200&nbsp;V two wire system from 1903 to 1950. 2,400&nbsp;V since 1950.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.railfaneurope.net/lamure/english/pres.html|title=ERS - Presentation, La Mure|author=|date=|website=www.railfaneurope.net|accessdate=10 April 2018}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 3,000\n| {{flagicon|USA}} USA\n| \n| [[Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad]]\n| {{convert|645|mi}} on two sections, dismantled 1974\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 3,500\n| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| Manchester\n| [[Bury to Holcombe Brook Line|Bury \u2013 Holcombe Brook]]\n| operated 1913\u20131918\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 6,000\n| {{flagicon|Russia}} Russia\n| &nbsp;\n| &nbsp;\n| experiments in the late 1970s (3,000 V DC lines)\n|}\n\n====AC voltage====\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:9%\" | Voltage\n! style=\"width:10%\" | Frequency\n! style=\"width:16%\" | Country\n! style=\"width:16%\" | Location\n! style=\"width:16%\" | Name of system\n! style=\"width:33%\" | Notes\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 5,500\n| {{frac|16|2|3}}&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Murnau am Staffelsee|Murnau]]\n| [[Ammergau Railway]] \n| 1905\u20131955, after 1955 15 kV, 16.7&nbsp;Hz\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| rowspan=2| 6,250\n| rowspan=2| 50&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| [[London]], [[Essex]], [[Hertfordshire|Herts]]\n| Great Eastern suburban lines\n| Great Eastern suburban lines from Liverpool Street [[London]], 1950s\u2013c1980 (converted to 25&nbsp;kV)\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| [[Glasgow]]\n| Glasgow suburban lines\n| Sections of the [[North Clyde Line]] and [[Cathcart Circle Line]] from 1960-1970s\n|-style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 6,300\n| 25&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Hamburg]]\n| [[Hamburg S-Bahn]]\n| Operated with AC 1907\u20131955. Used both AC and DC (1,200 V 3rd rail) 1940\u20131955.\n|-\n| 6,500\n| rowspan=2| 25&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|Austria}} Austria\n| [[Sankt P\u00f6lten]]\n| [[Mariazellerbahn]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 6,600\n| {{flagicon|Norway}} Norway\n| [[Orkdal]]\n| [[Thamshavnbanen]]\n| &nbsp;\n|-\n| 6,600\n| 50&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Cologne Lowland]]\n| [[:de:Hambachbahn|Hambachbahn]] and [[:de:Nord-S\u00fcd-Bahn (Garzweiler)|Nord-S\u00fcd-Bahn]]\n| transports [[lignite]] from [[open-pit mine]]s to powerplants. Owned by [[RWE]].\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| rowspan=2| 6,700\n| rowspan=2| 25&nbsp;Hz\n| rowspan=2| {{flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n| [[Morecambe branch line]]\n| [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] to [[Heysham]]\n| 1908\u20131951<br />Converted to 25&nbsp;kV 50&nbsp;Hz as a test bed for the future main line electrification system\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| [[South London line]]\n| [[London Victoria station]] to [[London Bridge station]]\n| 1909\u20131928<br />Converted to 660&nbsp;V (later 750&nbsp;V) DC third-rail supply\n<!--see: Garry Keenor CEng MIET, 'Overhead Line Electrification for Railways', 5th Edition, 2018, pp. 20, 22-->\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 8&nbsp;kV\n| rowspan=2| 25&nbsp;Hz\n| {{flagicon|Germany}} Germany\n| [[Karlsruhe]]\n| [[Alb Valley Railway]] \n| 1911\u20131966, today using 750 V DC\n|- style=\"background:#fee;\"\n| 10&nbsp;kV\n| {{flagicon|Netherlands}} [[Netherlands]]\n| [[The Hague]] - [[Rotterdam]]\n| [[Hofpleinlijn]]\n| from 1908, in 1926 converted to 1,500 DC, In 2006 replaced by 750 V DC light r